# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1895-in-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the years 1845 to 1868 throughout the world.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At its December 1868 annual meeting, the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) permitted professional clubs.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twelve existing members did "go pro" and constitute the professional field for 1869.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1868 season records for 98 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 15 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors" (not marked), all of the 1869 "pros" (*), all 14 member clubs with at least twelve wins on record, and a few others.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the seven listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At least four Association clubs not listed here would someday try professionalism: Riverside of Portsmouth, Ohio (1870); Kekionga of Fort Wayne, Indiana (1871); Middletown of Mansfield, Connecticut (1872); Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey (1873).
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Meanwhile, only two brand new professional baseball clubs would be established in the next three years, the Chicago White Stockings for 1870 and the Boston Red Stockings for 1871.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Their commercial origins may be related to their survival alone by 1877, and on to 2010, while all of their rivals with older and amateur roots fell away.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1867 season records for 89 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 17 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 13 member clubs with at least fourteen wins on record, and a few others.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the nine listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks ten clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Excelsior of Chicago and Buckeye of Cincinnati are listed because they were probably the strongest teams in the west after the Cincinnati Red Stockings.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1866 season records for 58 of 93 association members, said to be complete for games between two member clubs.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 20 of that season's teams "major" including three old New York rivals of the Knickerbockers.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 14 members with at least eight wins on record, and a few others.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the fifteen listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks eight clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869, three seasons later.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the preceding 1865 season Marshall Wright lists 30 members with supposedly complete records for most of them.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twenty-two of the thirty were in Greater New York.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 19 teams "major" in the first season that he covers: sixteen of the members and three others (Lowell, Harvard, and Camden).
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] No one traveled much and membership was still depressed by the Civil War.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] There had been 59 delegates at the March 1860 annual meeting, and 55 at the next annual meeting that December (on a new baseball calendar), who thereby intended to play during the 1861 season that the war curtailed.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Nine of 59 and eleven of 55 were from outside Greater New York.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1869 throughout the world.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] At its December 1868 meeting the NABBP permitted professional clubs for the first time.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] There had been no professional clubs outside the Association, and no brand new professional clubs were established for 1869.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Rather, the entire first-year effect of the change was that twelve existing members declared professional status.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] All of them had fielded at least regionally strong teams in 1868 and most if not all had compensated at least some of their players.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Cincinnati Red Stockings were first to sign an all-salary team, ten men for eight months.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] From the west, the strongest team in Cleveland also joined the pro field.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] From the eastern corridor there were ten including all of the one-time champions and claimants.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Otherwise the record of professional matches (see table) is remarkable for its balance, relative to the records of the stronger teams during the amateur era and to most of the following pro seasons.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Irvingtons did not travel, or win; after July they played only two matches with the Mutuals (four in all).
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Forest City of Cleveland did not travel far, only to Cincinnati and upstate New York.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Those two did not face each other or any of the three teams standing just above them.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] That imbalance, typical of the time, contributed to the losing records of all five.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Weaker teams were weaker gate attractions with less incentive and almost always less ability to travel.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Irvingtons disbanded and the Keystones returned to amateur ranks, but all the others remained in the professional field for 1870.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Indeed, all but Cincinnati remained in operation at least to 1872.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The amateur ranks during 1869 probably included some clubs who compensated their players by traditional methods such as division of the gate receipts (as Spalding said of Rockford by the end of the decade).
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Four of the amateurs would "go pro" in 1870, including the Forest City of Rockford, Illinois, with some success.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The professional field was relatively strong in 1869 and its weaker teams did not play many games.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Forest Citys did not beat any pro teams, but they played only four matches with Cincinnati, losing three by twenty runs and one by merely 14–15 on July 24.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] (They traveled no further than Detroit and Ohio while eastern pros also traveled no further than Ohio, home of their westernmost rivals.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Stars of Brooklyn, led by pitcher Candy Cummings, won 2 of 7 matches with pro teams, beating the Mutuals 26–12 on June 19 and the visiting Olympics of Washington 49–11 on July 19.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] They lost five to the Mutuals and Atlantics by only 28 runs, total margin.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Harvard college won 1 of 6 against pros, beating the powerful Athletics of Philadelphia 35–21 on July 9; the next day they lost a close one to the much weaker Keystones.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Against amateurs Star won fourteen with one defeat; Harvard won thirteen with one draw.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Next season they would win six each against the slightly larger pro field.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Lowell of Boston, listed among the major teams by Bill Ryczek, played three fairly close game against the pros, losing 21–26 to the Mutuals, 9–29 to undefeated Red Stockings, and 33–38 to the Eckfords.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Pastime of Baltimore won 2 of 9 against pro teams, including 1 of 4 local matches Maryland and one with the Troy Haymakers.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Olympics, Mutuals, Athletics, and Keystones beat them four teams by only 32 runs, total margin.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey beat Irvington 16–15 and lost twice to the Eckfords.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] These six amateur teams barely faced each other on the field: Lowell lost six to its local rival Harvard and one to Star (July 5, the Fourth being a Sunday that year).
[src:1895-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Harvard toured for ten days but played only the professional Eckfords in New York City.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Ten of the twelve professional clubs from 1869 remained in that field for 1870, all except Keystone of Philadelphia and Irvington, New Jersey, from Greater New York.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The five newcomers were Union of Morrisania, now in New York City; Tri-Mountain of Boston; Riverside of Portsmouth, Ohio; Forest City of Rockford, Illinois; and the Chicago White Stockings, the only brand new club.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Union was a founding member from the 1857 convention and Forest City had been one of the strongest amateurs remaining in 1869.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The records of the teams in professional matches, ranked by wins (see table), reveal three groups of five with sharp outlines.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] A big group of thirteen and a little of group of two are equally clear, considering the numbers of defeats, pro matches, and all matches (not shown), and are supported by the subsequent history.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The two more ambitious newcomers played only a few pro matches and never returned to the professional field.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Mighty Cincinnati and venerable Union also shut down after this season.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] All the others joined the new professional association established that winter (NAPBBP), seven as founding members and four in 1872 or 1873.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The Mutuals, Athletics, and Chicago White Stockings survived to found the National League in 1876.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Four amateur teams defeated professionals more than once and two of them demonstrated that they were as strong as middling pros.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Harvard college fielded its strongest team, which toured nationally in the summer and won 6 of 16 against professional teams all season.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Star of Brooklyn, featuring Hall of Fame pitcher Candy Cummings, won 6 of 13 against pros.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Pastime of Baltimore won 4 of 24 including 1 of 4 with the Troy Haymakers, 1 of 2 with Olympic, and 2 of 5 with Maryland.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The Pastimes lost badly to Harvard and won one of three close matches with the Stars.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey won 2 of 8, both at the expense of venerable Eckford; the Resolutes remained in operation until a failed venture into the professional field in 1873.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek lists Lowell of Boston and the Keystone of Philadelphia (pro in 1869) among the major teams.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] They did not defeat any professionals but showed strength comparable to Pastime, Resolute, and the weaker pros.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Considering the professionals in three groups of five ranked by wins in pro matches (see table), the stronger pros won 37 of 41 against the six amateur teams covered here; the middling pros won 13 of 18; the weaker pros won 6 of 15.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Here are the records of those amateurs against the pros.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] One of the elite professional teams, the Athletics of Philadelphia won eight matches with Harvard, Lowell, Keystone, and Pastime, with 20 to 34 runs scored and 11- to 22-run margins.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Three amateur clubs of 1870 would later enter the all-professional National Association for one season each: Kekionga of Fort Wayne, Indiana in 1871; Mansfield of Middletown, Connecticut in 1872; Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey in 1873.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Harvard continued to field strong amateur teams, but amateurs would not again hold their own with middling pros.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The Stars won a championship in 1871 under the new all-amateur Association (NAABBP), before Candy Cummings joined the pros in 1872.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1871-in-baseball] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1872-brooklyn-eckfords-season] The **Brooklyn Eckfords** played their first and only season of professional baseball in 1872 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1872-brooklyn-eckfords-season] They finished ninth in the league with a record of 3-26.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1872-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1872 throughout the world.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1873-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1873 throughout the world.
[src:1895-in-baseball/1895-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1895 throughout the world.
